{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-84d7476f7bac0d26", "type": "tool_result", "content": "<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (49.4KB). Full output saved to: /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/60907d1c-0e12-4b9b-9404-6d2b685917c1/tool-results/btt2i2a01.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\nGoodbye Equal Error Rate, Hello Local Information Disclosure: Evaluating Voice Anonymisation against 1-to-N Linkage Threats Report GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! Learn more × Back to arXiv License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 arXiv:2607.06259v1 [eess.AS] 07 Jul 2026 Šterns Drossos Fernandes Bäckström Palamidessi Goodbye Equal Error Rate, Hello Local Information Disclosure: Evaluating Voice Anonymisation against 1-to-N Linkage Threats Dāvis Konstantinos Natasha Tom Catuscia 1 Aalto University, Finland; 2 Inria, France; 3 Nokia, Finland; 4 Macquarie University, Australia davis.sterns@aalto.fi, konstantinos.drosos@nokia.fi, natasha.fernandes@mq.edu.au, tom.backstrom@aalto.fi, catuscia@lix.polytechnique.fr Abstract Voice anonymisation aims to protect speaker identity. Currently, its empirical privacy evaluation heavily relies on the Equal Error Rate (EER). Originally designed for biometric verification, EER aggregates scores globally, implicitly assuming an attacker is only trying to verify if two specific voice samples match (a 1 1 -to- 1 1 comparison). This introduces a threat model mismatch with real-world database linkage attacks, where an attacker searches across a fixed set of N N enrolled identities (a 1 1 -to- N N closed-set search), allowing global averages to obscure localised privacy failures. While recent 1 1 -to- N N metrics address this aggregation issue, they abstract away the magnitude of the biometric evidence. In this paper, we propose a modular, information-theoretic evaluation framework explicitly designed for the 1 1 -to- N N linkage threat model. Within this framework, our core metric, Local Information Disclosure (LID), quantifies the exact privacy loss of a single trial utterance in bits by calibrating its raw similarity scores into the attacker's posterior confidence for each enrolled identity. Evaluating top-performing system\n...\n</persisted-output>", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "60907d1c-0e12-4b9b-9404-6d2b685917c1", "uuid": "ca7611a9-905f-4a71-bdac-280aff6a731f", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T14:43:17.847Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "Goodbye Equal Error Rate, Hello Local Information Disclosure: Evaluating Voice Anonymisation against 1-to-N Linkage Threats Report GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! Learn more × Back to arXiv License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 arXiv:2607.06259v1 [eess.AS] 07 Jul 2026 Šterns Drossos Fernandes Bäckström Palamidessi Goodbye Equal Error Rate, Hello Local Information Disclosure: Evaluating Voice Anonymisation against 1-to-N Linkage Threats Dāvis Konstantinos Natasha Tom Catuscia 1 Aalto University, Finland; 2 Inria, France; 3 Nokia, Finland; 4 Macquarie University, Australia davis.sterns@aalto.fi, konstantinos.drosos@nokia.fi, natasha.fernandes@mq.edu.au, tom.backstrom@aalto.fi, catuscia@lix.polytechnique.fr Abstract Voice anonymisation aims to protect speaker identity. Currently, its empirical privacy evaluation heavily relies on the Equal Error Rate (EER). Originally designed for biometric verification, EER aggregates scores globally, implicitly assuming an attacker is only trying to verify if two specific voice samples match (a 1 1 -to- 1 1 comparison). This introduces a threat model mismatch with real-world database linkage attacks, where an attacker searches across a fixed set of N N enrolled identities (a 1 1 -to- N N closed-set search), allowing global averages to obscure localised privacy failures. While recent 1 1 -to- N N metrics address this aggregation issue, they abstract away the magnitude of the biometric evidence. In this paper, we propose a modular, information-theoretic evaluation framework explicitly designed for the 1 1 -to- N N linkage threat model. Within this framework, our core metric, Local Information Disclosure (LID), quantifies the exact privacy loss of a single trial utterance in bits by calibrating its raw similarity scores into the attacker's posterior confidence for each enrolled identity. Evaluating top-performing systems from the VoicePrivacy 2024 Challenge reveals that systems exhibiting near-perfect EERs ( \\qty 48%) can still suffer from localised vulnerabilities with worst-case disclosures reaching 1 1 bit per trial utterance (effectively doubling the attacker's success rate over a random guess). We demonstrate that adopting localised privacy metrics is essential for capturing worst-case risks and aligning with strict privacy regulations. keywords: Voice Anonymisation, Speech Privacy, Empirical Privacy Evaluation, Linkage Attacks 1 Introduction Speech signals carry sensitive biometric information, making the widespread collection and processing of voice data a significant privacy risk. To protect the privacy of speakers and to comply with legal frameworks such as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), voice anonymisation has emerged as a method for suppressing speaker identity while preserving linguistic utility [ backstrom2025privacy ] . While certain privacy-enhancing technologies offer formal, mathematical guarantees (e.g., differential privacy [ dwork2006calibrating ] ), extending these theoretical frameworks to the complex, high-dimensional modern generative voice models remains an open challenge. Consequently, current system performance must be evaluated empirically by simulating concrete adversarial attacks against the anonymised data. The standard empirical evaluation paradigm, popularised by the VoicePrivacy Challenge (VPC) [ tomashenko2020introducing ] , relies on simulating linkage attacks. In this scenario, an attacker computes similarity scores by comparing anonymised trial utterances with known identities in an enrolment database. 1 1 1 These terms originate from biometric access control: a user first provides enrolment utterances to register or “enrol” their identity in the system, and later provides a “trial” sample when attempting to be verified or recognised. By observing the attacker's success rate across numerous trials, auditors can estimate the practical privacy level of the system. To establish a clear threat model, this paper focuses strictly on the risk of linking independent, isolated trial utterances to a known database. We do not address other adversarial objectives, such as inferring attributes like demographic traits [ meyer2023voicepat ] , or exploiting longitudinal leakage, where an attacker might leverage temporal patterns across multiple interconnected sessions [ vauquier2025legally ] . Under this adversarial framework, privacy evaluation can be described as a two-step process: 1. Score generation: Simulating a specific attacker, typically an automatic speaker verification (ASV) system, to compute a matrix of similarity scores between the anonymised trial utterances and the known enrolment profiles. 2. Score evaluation: Applying a metric 2 2 2 While a mathematical metric formally denotes a pairwise distance function, we adopt the standard colloquial usage of the privacy community, using the term to describe an aggregate statistical measure of system-level risk. to the resulting similarity score matrix to estimate the overall privacy risk. While the speech privacy community has actively focused on creating more sophisticated attackers for the score generation phase (as highlighted by the recent VoicePrivacy Attacker Challenge [ tomashenko2025first ] ), the score evaluation phase still frequently relies on global metrics originally designed for speaker verification [ champion2023anonymizing ] . Metrics such as the EER, the Cost of Log-Likelihood Ratio ( C llr C_{\\text{llr}} ), Empirical Linkability ( D ↔ D_{\\leftrightarrow} ), and the ZEBRA framework evaluate the statistical separability of isolated mated and non-mated score distributions [ maouche2020comparative ] . This reliance introduces a threat model mismatch between the two steps: we simulate an attacker who possesses an enrolment database and compares a single trial utterance against all enrolments to find the best match (a 1 1 -to- N N search). Yet, by globally pooling these scores into two sets, current metrics evaluate the system as if the attacker were independently guessing whether a single, contextless similarity score belongs to a mated or non-mated pair (a 1 1 -to- 1 1 decision). As we demonstrate in Section 4 , this mismatch allows standard metrics like the EER to theoretically report a ``safe'' \\qty 50 error rate even when a simple 1 1 -to- N N linkage attack achieves \\qty 100 linkage accuracy on the exact same scores. Alternative score evaluation approaches have recently been proposed to address this aggregation issue, yet to the best of our knowledge, no existing evaluation metric fully aligns with the 1 1 -to- N N threat model simulated in the score generation phase. Similarity Rank Disclosure (SRD) [ backstrom2026privacy ] preserves the 1 1 -to- N N relational context, but evaluates the success of an attacker who only obtains an ordered list of speakers. Conversely, the Legally Validated Evaluation Framework [ vauquier2025legally ] accounts for probability but relies on the assumption that the attacker makes a forced-choice commitment to a single highest-scoring profile. This highlights an unresolved challenge: evaluating the true risk of an attacker who observes the complete 1 1 -to- N N vector of similarity scores for a given trial, utilising both the relational context and the magnitude of the evidence. To address this, we introduce a modular, information-theoretic evaluation framework explicitly designed for the 1 1 -to- N N linkage threat model. The framework takes the complete similarity matrix generated by the attacker and operates in two sequential stages. First, an inner aggregator evaluates the information disclosure of each specific trial. This is achieved by calibrating the raw scores into posterior probabilities, and condensing the entire vector of candidate scores for a single trial into one information-theoretic score: the Local Information Disclosure (LID). This captures the strength of the evidence that the attacker gained (or the amount of its confusion). Second, an outer aggregator combines these trial-level LID values to construct various global metrics, such as average information disclosure, positive information disclosure rate, and maximum observed disclosure, ensuring that per-trial vulnerabilities remain visible. The contributions of this paper are as follows: • Demonstration of the threat model mismatch: we examine how existing privacy metrics behave under a 1 1 -to- N N linkage attack. We demonstrate how global metrics obscure local vulnerabilities, and how recent alternative metrics misalign with the attacker's full evidentiary profile, motivating the need for a new approach. • Information-theoretic evaluation framework: we propose a novel privacy metric that quantifies exact information disclosure in bits. Grounded in pointwise mutual information, our framework measures how much information an attacker gains about a target identity after observing a single trial utterance. • Empirical unmasking of VPC 2024 systems: we validate our framework against voice anonymisation baselines and top submissions from the VoicePrivacy 2024 Challenge. We reveal that systems exhibiting near-perfect EERs still suffer from localised vulnerabilities, with maximum information disclosures reaching 1 1 bit, effectively doubling the attacker's success rate over random chance. 2 Related Work The VPC provides a standard benchmarking framework for empirical evaluation of speech privacy by simulating state-of-the-art ASV attackers. These adversaries typically rely on deep neural architectures, such as ECAPA-TDNN [ desplanques2020ecapa ] and x-vectors [ snyder2018x ] , to extract speaker embeddings from the audio. To establish a database of known identities, the embeddings of multiple enrolment utterances are averaged to construct enrolment profiles . The adversary then evaluates the similarity between these enrolment profiles and individual trial utterances using scoring backends such as probabilistic linear discriminant analysis or cosine similarity. To systematically evaluate vulnerabilities, the VPC defines a hierarchy of threat models based on attacker knowledge and resources [ tomashenko2024voiceprivacy ] . An ignorant attacker is unaware of the anonymisation; they use an ASV trained on original speech and compare original enrolment profiles against anonymised trials. A lazy-informed attacker is aware of the anonymisation process and aligns the domains by anonymising the enrolment data, but their ASV model remains trained on the original, non-anonymised speech. Finally, the semi-informed attacker represents the most serious threat considered: they anonymise the enrolment data and retrain the embedding extractor with the anonymised ASV training corpus to explicitly exploit the residual speaker-discriminative properties of the anonymised domain. 2.1 Verification under 1-to-1 threat models In typical evaluation protocols, privacy metrics often frame the attack as a binary hypothesis test. To perform this evaluation, the similarity scores generated across all trials are aggregated into two distinct distributions: a mated set representing same-speaker comparisons, and a non-mated set representing different-speaker comparisons. Privacy is then quantified by assessing the statistical separability of these two sets (as visualised in Figure 1 ). Figure 1: Score distributions for three privacy scenarios. (a) Unlinkable: The mated (green) and non-mated (blue) distributions overlap completely, preventing speaker discrimination. (b) Semi-linkable: The distributions diverge, creating a ``tail'' of high scores that leaks identity information. (c) Fully linkable: The distributions are separable, allowing for trivial re-identification. To quantify the extent of this overlap, empirical evaluations frequently employ the EER [ tomashenko2024voiceprivacy ] . It is defined as the error rate at the specific decision boundary where the False Acceptance Rate (non-mated comparisons scoring above this boundary) equals the False Rejection Rate (mated comparisons scoring below it). In an ideal anonymisation scenario with completely overlapping distributions (Figure 1 a), the EER would be \\qty 50, whereas in a fully linkable scenario (Figure 1 c), it drops to \\qty 0. Empirical Linkability ( D ↔ D_{\\leftrightarrow} ) [ gomez2017general ] measures privacy geometrically by calculating the absolute difference between the probability density functions of the two distributions. The Cost of Log-Likelihood Ratio ( C llr C_{\\text{llr}} ) [ brummer2006application ] applies an information-theoretic approach, evaluating the system based on calibrated log-likelihoods. Finally, the ZEBRA framework [ nautsch2020privacy ] extends this probabilistic evaluation by calculating the expected privacy loss across all possible prior knowledge states an attacker might possess. Structurally, these metrics align with a 1 1 -to- 1 1 verification threat model: they model an adversary whose objective is to observe a single similarity score and determine whether it corresponds to a mated or non-mated pair. 2.2 Identification under 1-to-N threat models Recent methodologies adopt a more realistic threat model, recognising that real-world attackers often compare a single intercepted utterance against an entire database of known enrolled identities simultaneously. SRD [ backstrom2026privacy ] evaluates the system by simulating a closed-set linkage task. For each trial utterance, the metric sorts all N N available enrolment profiles based on their computed similarity scores. By aggregating these rankings across the evaluation dataset, the method estimates the empirical probability γ k \\gamma_{k} that the target identity appears at rank k k . The privacy loss is then quantified as the reduction in uncertainty (in bits) relative to a random guess, defined as log 2 ⁡ ( N ⋅ γ k ) \\log_{2}(N\\cdot\\gamma_{k}) . Structurally, SRD models an adversary who observes the ordinal ranking of the candidates, independent of the absolute score values. In practice, this reflects a scenario where an attacker extracts a prioritised shortlist of the most likely matches, ranked from highest to lowest probability. Bridging empirical technical evaluation with regulatory compliance, Legally Validated Evaluation Framework [ vauquier2025legally ] maps GDPR definitions (the risks of Singling Out and Linkability) directly to the ASV outputs. In their framework, empirical linkability is evaluated by calculating the probability that the similarity score of the mated pair is strictly greater than the maximum score among all non-mated pairs in a given trial. This formulation aligns with a threat model in which the adversary is an automated system that must commit to the single highest-scoring enrolment profile as the target identity. 3 Adversarial Privacy Evaluation Framework In this section, we define the linkage-based adversarial framework that generates the 1 1 -to- N N similarity matrix. A core principle of this framework is that privacy is not a static, intrinsic property of an anonymisation algorithm . Instead, privacy is the measurable outcome of the interaction between a protection mechanism, a specific adversary, and the underlying speech dataset. Consequently, swapping the attacker, the protector, or the dataset alters the evaluation outcome. For instance, as demonstrated by Panariello et al. [ panariello2025risks ] , evaluating a system against a mismatched attack model creates an illusion of high privacy. This is, however, caused by the failure of the attacker rather than a genuinely robust defence. 3.1 Threat model specification Following the scenario of use scheme proposed by Rahman et al. [ rahman2024scenario ] , we define the operational boundaries of the evaluation. Table 1 contrasts the objectives, opportunities, and resources of the attacker and the protector. We assume the attacker possesses a database of enrolment speech samples mapped to known identities, which are obtained, for example, from public biometric datasets, compromised databases, or social media profiles. Upon intercepting an anonymised trial sample, the attacker's objective is to search this database and link the trial sample to the correct identity. Conversely, the protector acts as a data controller who selects and deploys the specific anonymisation method used to protect the trial speech, aiming to prevent this identity linkage while preserving some specific downstream utility of the data. To accommodate the different threat models defined by the VPC, advanced capabilities are detailed as optional extensions in Table 1 . Specifically, the ignorant model assumes default access, the lazy-informed model requires knowledge of the deployed anonymisation system, and the semi-informed model demands both this knowledge and the computational resources necessary to train adapted ASV models. Table 1: Scenario of Use Specification for Voice Linkage Attacks (adapted from [ rahman2024scenario ] ) Dimension Attacker model (attack on privacy) Protector model (protection of privacy) Objective Successfully link an isolated trial voice sample to a specific identity within a known database. Defence objective: Prevent speaker re-identification. Utility objective: Ensure the anonymised speech preserves linguistic content and necessary downstream features. Opportunity Access to the target speaker's intercepted trial audio. Access to a multi-speaker enrolment database that includes enrolment utterances of the target speaker alongside other distinct identities. [Optional: Knowledge of the deployed anonymisation system.] Full control over the data pipeline to deploy the anonymisation system prior to the audio being intercepted or released. Knowledge that the attacker will employ ASV-based linkage methods. Additional Resources Publicly available speech datasets. [Optional: Finite computing power to train adapted ASV models.] Finite computing power. Publicly available speech datasets and baseline ASV models for evaluation. 3.2 Formal components Based on this threat model, we formalise the three interacting components of the evaluation: the dataset, the protector, and the attacker. 3.2.1 Dataset To evaluate speech privacy under this adversarial privacy evaluation framework, we require speech datasets containing multiple speakers, each with multiple utterances. Regardless of the attacker's assumed knowledge level, the auditor's goal is to measure the maximum identity information that can be extracted from the resulting scores. To accurately map the attacker's raw similarity scores into likelihood ratios, the auditor requires two distinct datasets with non-overlapping speaker identities: a development set ( 𝒟 dev \\mathcal{D}_{\\text{dev}} ) to calibrate the scoring mechanism, and an evaluation set ( 𝒟 eval \\mathcal{D}_{\\text{eval}} ) to compute the final privacy disclosure metrics. Each of these datasets is further partitioned into an enrolment set ( ℰ \\mathcal{E} ) and a trial set ( 𝒯 \\mathcal{T} ). The enrolment set ( ℰ \\mathcal{E} ) contains multiple enrolment utterances per speaker, which are averaged to form stable identity profiles. The trial set contains distinct utterances from those same speakers, representing the intercepted audio samples. 3 3 3 While baseline VPC protocols include “impostor” trials without enrolled identities to test open-set rejection, our framework explicitly models a closed-set 1 1 -to- N N linkage attack. Thus, we only use trials that possess a target identity in ℰ \\mathcal{E} . 3.2.2 Protector We define the voice anonymisation mechanism as a function f f that transforms an input utterance x x into an anonymised utterance x ^ = f ​ ( x ) \\hat{x}=f(x) , designed to suppress speaker identity while preserving utility. When applied to a set, f f anonymises all utterances in the set. 3.2.3 Attacker We model the attacker as a linkage function L L that computes a similarity score s s between a trial utterance τ i ∈ 𝒯 \\tau_{i}\\in\\mathcal{T} and a set of enrolment utterances ε j ⊂ ℰ \\varepsilon_{j}\\subset\\mathcal{E} , where ε j \\varepsilon_{j} consists of all utterances of a specific person j j . Higher values of s s correspond to a higher confidence of an identity match. Depending on the attacker's knowledge level (defined in Section 2 ), the inputs to L L are modified: • Ignorant: s = L ​ ( ε j , f ​ ( τ i ) ) s=L(\\varepsilon_{j},f(\\tau_{i})) . • Lazy / Semi-Informed: s = L ​ ( f ​ ( ε j ) , f ​ ( τ i ) ) s=L(f(\\varepsilon_{j}),f(\\tau_{i})) (with the semi-informed L L additionally fine-tuned on anonymised data). 3.3 Score generation: the similarity score matrices The attacker simulates a closed-set search independently for 𝒟 dev \\mathcal{D}_{\\text{dev}} and 𝒟 eval \\mathcal{D}_{\\text{eval}} . For each trial utterance τ i ∈ 𝒯 \\tau_{i}\\in\\mathcal{T} , the attacker exhaustively queries the linkage function L L against all available enrolment profiles in ℰ \\mathcal{E} . This execution yields two separate similarity matrices: a development matrix 𝐒 dev ∈ ℝ T ′ × N ′ \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{dev}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T^{\\prime}\\times N^{\\prime}} and an evaluation matrix 𝐒 eval ∈ ℝ T × N \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{eval}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times N} , where T T and N N denote the number of trial utterances and enrolled identities in the evaluation set, respectively, and T ′ T^{\\prime} and N ′ N^{\\prime} represent the corresponding dimensions for the development set. In both matrices, each row represents the complete evidence for a given trial utterance obtained by the attacker. The generation of such matrices has previously proven effective for visually exposing speaker-level privacy vulnerabilities [ noe2020speech ] . 4 Threat Model Alignment in Privacy Evaluation When an evaluation metric's underlying assumptions misalign with the simulated attack, privacy estimates can distort real-world risk. In this section, we illustrate how existing evaluation paradigms misalign with the 1 1 -to- N N linkage threat model. 4.1 Global thresholds vs. localised search Because standard binary metrics assess global separability, they inherently evaluate a 1 1 -to- 1 1 verification threat model. To illustrate why applying this to a 1 1 -to- N N linkage attack misrepresents risk, consider the hypothetical 4 × 4 4\\times 4 similarity matrix S S generated by comparing four trial utterances ( τ 1 \\tau_{1} to τ 4 \\tau_{4} ) against four enrolment profiles ( ε 1 \\varepsilon_{1} to ε 4 \\varepsilon_{4} ), with mated scores in bold : S = [ 0.9 0.8 0.8 0.8 0.7 0.6 0.6 0.6 0.4 0.5 0.4 0.4 0.2 0.2 0.3 0.2 ] . S=\\begin{bmatrix}\\textbf{0.9}&0.8&0.8&0.8\\\\ \\textbf{0.7}&0.6&0.6&0.6\\\\ 0.4&\\textbf{0.5}&0.4&0.4\\\\ 0.2&0.2&\\textbf{0.3}&0.2\\end{bmatrix}. (1) A hypothetical attacker operating under a localised 1 1 -to- N N search could simply select the maximum score per row, successfully linking every utterance with \\qty 100 accuracy . However, evaluating the matrix with a binary metric yields an EER of exactly \\qty 50 , a value traditionally interpreted as absolute privacy. This is because the metric evaluates the matrix by stripping away its row-wise context. When aggregated, the set of mated comparisons { 0.9 , 0.7 , 0.5 , 0.3 } \\{0.9,0.7,0.5,0.3\\} and the set of non-mated comparisons { 0.8 [ × 3 ] , 0.6 [ × 3 ] , 0.4 [ × 3 ] , 0.2 [ × 3 ] } \\{0.8_{[\\times 3]},0.6_{[\\times 3]},0.4_{[\\times 3]},0.2_{[\\times 3]}\\} overlap significantly. If a decision boundary is drawn at 0.55 0.55 , exactly half of the mated comparisons fall below it (a \\qty 50 False Rejection Rate) and half of the non-mated comparisons fall above it (a \\qty 50 False Acceptance Rate). The metric's reliance on global variance entirely masks the local per-trial vulnerability. 4.2 Evidentiary weight in localised search While more privacy-centred metrics resolve this global aggregation issue, their specific assumptions about the attacker's behaviour may be misaligned. By reducing continuous scores to ordinal ranks, SRD preserves the row-wise context but abstracts away the biometric margin. For instance, SRD evaluates the trial vectors [ 0.90 , 0.10 , 0.10 ] [\\textbf{0.90},0.10,0.10] and [ 0.50 , 0.45 , 0.45 ] [\\textbf{0.50},0.45,0.45] as mathematically identical Rank-1 observations. Yet, to an attacker analysing these scores, the former scenario yields high confidence due to the significant contrast between scores, whereas the narrow margin in the latter provides weak evidentiary support for a definitive linkage. Similarly, the Legally Validated Evaluation Framework anchors the localised evaluation in a forced-choice assumption. By strictly measuring the empirical probability that the mated score is the highest, the metric assumes that the attacker must definitively commit to the top-ranked candidate, regardless of the margin. In practice, adversaries can leverage the weight of the observed similarity scores. If the scores for several profiles are very similar, the attacker remains uncertain. Conversely, a large margin between the highest score and the rest gives the attacker high confidence in a successful linkage. Thus, to rigorously evaluate an adversary possessing the full trial vector, we require a metric that explicitly considers the full observed evidence. 5 Proposed Privacy Evaluation Framework To quantify the information an attacker extracts from the observed similarity scores, we propose a modular, information-theoretic evaluation framework. This framework processes the two similarity matrices generated in Step 1 ( 𝐒 dev \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{dev}} and 𝐒 eval \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{eval}} ) through three sequential stages: (1) Score Calibration, (2) Inner Aggregation (per-trial local leakage), and (3) Outer Aggregation (global risk profiling). 5.1 Step 1: Calibration (bridging scores to confidence) Raw similarity scores produced by the linkage function L L (e.g., cosine similarities) are domain-dependent and lack intrinsic statistical meaning. To quantify the actual evidentiary weight of an attack, we must calibrate these raw scores into probabilistically meaningful Log-Likelihood Ratios (LLRs). We achieve this in two steps: row-wise normalisation followed by logistic calibration. 5.1.1 Row-wise contextual normalisation. We empirically observe that, particularly for strong anonymisation mechanisms, the absolute magnitude of a similarity score is less informative than its relative distinctiveness among competing enrolment profiles. Therefore, for a given similarity matrix, we first compute the row-wise z-score (often referred to as T-norm in biometrics [ auckenthaler2000score ] ) for each trial i i and enrolment profile j j : s ^ i , j = s i , j − μ i σ i , \\hat{s}_{i,j}=\\frac{s_{i,j}-\\mu_{i}}{\\sigma_{i}}, (2) where μ i \\mu_{i} and σ i \\sigma_{i} are the mean and standard deviation of the raw scores across the N N enrolled identities for trial i i . 5.1.2 Logistic calibration. Next, we map these standardised scores to log-posterior odds using a univariate logistic regression model (Platt scaling [ platt1999probabilistic ] ). Furthermore, because a 1 1 -to- N N linkage attack suffers from extreme class imbalance, where the number of non-mated pairs ( N non-mated N_{\\text{non-mated}} ) in the development set far exceeds the number of mated pairs ( N mated N_{\\text{mated}} ) (there is only one mated score per trial), the posterior probabilities learned by the model are naturally skewed. To isolate the pure evidentiary value (the LLR) independently of this prior distribution, we subtract the prior log-odds from the logistic regression output: LLR i , j = ( w ​ s ^ i , j + b ) − ln ⁡ ( N mated N non-mated ) , \\mathrm{LLR}_{i,j}=(w\\hat{s}_{i,j}+b)-\\ln\\left(\\frac{N_{\\text{mated}}}{N_{\\text{non-mated}}}\\right), (3) where w w and b b are the scalar weight and bias learned from fitting the logistic regression on 𝐒 dev \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{dev}} . Once learned, this calibration pipeline is applied to the evaluation data: 𝐒 eval \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{eval}} undergoes the identical row-wise normalisation before the parameters w w and b b are applied to generate the final evaluation LLRs. 5.2 Step 2: The inner aggregator (local leakage) The Inner Aggregator evaluates the exact information an attacker extracts from a single linkage attempt. For a given trial i i , the attacker attempts to determine the unknown identity of the speaker, modelled as a random variable I ∈ { 1 , 2 , … , N } I\\in\\{1,2,\\dots,N\\} . Let m i m_{i} be the ground-truth index of the target identity. Thus, the event I = m i I=m_{i} represents the scenario where the target identity is correctly determined. Let E i E_{i} represent the biometric evidence observed by the attacker for the trial i i . In practice, this evidence is the vector of LLRs (calibrated similarity scores) comparing the trial against the N N enrolled profiles. By applying the softmax function to the LLRs, the probability of correctly determining the target identity given the evidence is: P ​ ( I = m i ∣ E i ) = p i , m i = exp ⁡ ( LLR i , m i ) ∑ k = 1 N exp ⁡ ( LLR i , k ) . P(I=m_{i}\\mid E_{i})=p_{i,m_{i}}=\\frac{\\exp(\\mathrm{LLR}_{i,m_{i}})}{\\sum_{k=1}^{N}\\exp(\\mathrm{LLR}_{i,k})}. (4) Note that in this equation the bias b b and prior log-odds cancel out. Figure 2: Empirical distribution of the posterior probability assigned to the target identity ( p i , m i p_{i,m_{i}} ) across a dataset of evaluation trials. The red dotted line denotes the baseline prior probability of a random guess ( 1 / N 1/N , where N = 29 N=29 ). Figure 2 visualises the distribution of these posterior probabilities on real evaluation data. While these probabilities are useful for gaining insight into the attacker's performance, to strictly quantify the privacy loss, we must measure the exact reduction in the attacker's uncer", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/60907d1c-0e12-4b9b-9404-6d2b685917c1/tool-results/btt2i2a01.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 50628}}
